Black moves his rook out - not sure why
Opening a path for my Bishops

If I were Black, I would have done pawn to b4 instead, then when I used my a-column pawn to capture, use the Queen to take the white pawn, to avoid opening a path for white to take the rook and giving my queen some leverage in White's territory. Instead, from this move on, my Bishops get free reign of the board (basically).
Recapturing the pawn

Taking the unprotected pawn and putting my bishop in an advantageous position. It wasn't until just a minute ago (literally, as I'm typing this) that I realized that so far, Black's WSB has not moved at all - at this point, if I were black, I would do Bb7.

Taking the rook and threatening mate. Black has basically three moves at this point: a useless interposition by his WSB, interposing with his queen (and mate on the next move) or moving his king to e7 and possibly escaping mate, although if he had done that, I would have done Qd8+, forcing him to move his king to d6 and letting me take the queen, at which point, huge advantage for me. Black resigns here.
